The given code is trying to automate the login process for a website using Selenium WebDriver in Java. The issue is that the email input field is being sent to the website's login page instead of the Facebook login page.

To resolve this issue, we need to locate the Facebook login page and send the email input to the Facebook login page. We can use the following code to achieve this:
```java
// Create a new Firefox browser instance
FirefoxDriver driver = new FirefoxDriver();

// Navigate to the website
driver.get("http://www.example.com");

// Click the login button
driver.findElement(By.className("btnSignIn")).click();

// Click the Facebook login button
driver.findElement(By.className("facebookBtn")).click();

// Wait for the Facebook login page to load
WebDriverWait wait = new WebDriverWait(driver, 10);
wait.until(ExpectedConditions.visibilityOfElementLocated(By.id("email")));

// Enter the email address
driver.findElement(By.id("email")).sendKeys("selenium");

// Click the login button on the Facebook page
driver.findElement(By.id("login-button")).click();

// Close the browser
driver.quit();
```
In this code, we first create a new Firefox browser instance and navigate to the website. Then, we click the login button and wait for the Facebook login page to load. Once the page loads, we enter the email address and click the login button on the Facebook page. Finally, we close the browser.

Note that we use the `WebDriverWait` class to wait for the Facebook login page to load before entering the email address. We also use the `ExpectedConditions` class to locate the email input field by its ID.
